  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="NA396-kiḷavi">
            <p type="edition">1. itu tōḻi talaimakaṉai varaivu kaṭāyatu. 2. varaivuṇarttappaṭṭu āṟṟuc (EN, ER, ET, EV: āṟṟāḷāyc; C1: uṇarttappaṭṭāḷāy) colliyatūumām. 3. iravukkuṟi maṟuttatūumām.</p>
            <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante urged HIM for marriage. 2. It is also what was said, being able to bear it after being informed of the marriage. 3. It is also what refused a night tryst.</p>
            </div>
      <div xml:id="NA396">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            peytupō keḻili vaikumalai cērat</l>
<l>            tēṉṟūṅ kuyarvarai yaruvi yārppa</l>
<l>            vēṅkai tanta veṟpaṇi naṉṉāṭ</l>
<l>            poṉṉi ṉaṉṉa pūñciṉai tuḻaiik</l>
<l>            kamaḻtā tāṭiya kaviṉpeṟu tōkai</l>
<l>            pācaṟai mīmicaik kaṇaṅkoḷpu ñāyiṟ</l>
<l>            ṟuṟukati riḷaveyi luṇṇu nāṭa</l>
<l>            niṉmār paṇaṅkiya cella larunō</l>
<l>            yārkkunon turaikkō yāṉē paṉṉāṭ</l>
<l>            kāmar naṉicoṟ colli</l>
<l>            yēmameṉ ṟaruḷāy nīmayaṅ kiṉaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            O man from a land, where the young light of the rays coming from</l>
<l rend="indent">            the sun is absorbed by the peacock, with [its] group on the elevation of</l>
<l rend="indent">            green rocks, obtaining beauty when it played with the fragrant pollen</l>
<l rend="indent2">            after stirring the branches with gold-like flowers</l>
<l rend="indent2">            on the good day<note place="foot">The position of <term xml:lang="ta">nal nāḷ</term> as a specification of time is very awkward. We might consider reading two further adjectives to <term xml:lang="ta">pū</term> instead, <term xml:lang="ta">nāḷ</term> being a way of referring to the freshness of the blossom (i.e. opened that very day; cf. NA 301.2).</note> of the mountain’s decoration given by the Vēṅkai,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            while the clouds, going after raining,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            join the mountains to be kept [there],</l>
<l rend="indent3">            while waterfalls roar on the high mountains hung with honey[-combs],</l>
<l>        – to whom shall I achingly talk</l>
<l rend="indent2">            of the difficult pain of distress with which your chest has tormented me?</l>
<l rend="indent">            After speaking many<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">naṉi col</term>: here <term xml:lang="ta">naṉi</term> seems to be used in an attributive, not in an adverbial way.</note> desirous words, for many days,</l>
<l>        you [are] not considerate [in a way that gives] joy.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ēmam-eṉṟu</term>: I see here the strange intermediate case between an ideophone and an adverb often to be found with these <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ</term>-constructions.</note> You are changed.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mayaṅkiṉai</term>: tradition reads here that HE is confused (which implies that this is only temporarily - of course he will come and marry HER in the end), but the perfective aspect might as well suggest a more pronounced statement.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
